title: For Sale:  Browning Model 71 50 Alaskan For Sale
postcontent: Hello and thank you for checking out my riffle. Up for auction is a very nice Browning Model 71 lever action in .50 Alaskan, These rifles were orginally chambered in .348 Winchester. Gunsmiths wanted the Browning 71 due to its durability and strength when converting rifles to 50 Alaskan. This rifle has a half octagon half round barrel measuring at 34", an all steal Schnabel forend, the sights have not been clipped and the engraving on the barrel and action are beautiful. the stock also has a hidden compartment for holding 4 rounds. The .50 Alaskan is a wildcat cartridge developed by Harold Johnson and Harold Fuller of the Kenai Peninsula of Alaska in the 1950s. Johnson based the cartridge on the .348 Winchester in order to create a rifle capable of handling the large bears in Alaska. Design: Harold Johnson necked out the .348 Winchester case to accept a .510" diameter bullet, and Harold Fuller developed the barrel, marrying a .50 caliber barrel to an old Winchester Model 1886 rifle. Since the rifle was designed for use on Alaska’s great bears, Johnson cut 720-grain (47 g) boat-tail .50 BMG bullets in half, seating the 450-grain (29 g) rear half upside down in the fireformed .50-caliber case. It didn’t take Johnson long to find out that the 450-grain truncated shaped “solid” would shoot through a big brown bear from any direction, claiming in 1988, “I never recovered a slug from a bear or moose, no matter what angle the animal was shot at. Harold’s favorite load in the .50 Alaskan was 51.5 grains (3.34 g) of IMR-4198 with a Barnes 400-grain (26 g) flatnose ,jacketed bullet for about 2,100 ft/s (640 m/s) and just under 4,000 ft·lbf (5,400 J)of muzzle energy Shipping/handling is going to be $55 and insurance will be added at 1.75% of the item's value to cover potential damage or loss of the item in shipping. The price is for $1500 therefore, this item will still be subject to shipping and insurance charges. Because of additional paperwork and time to process the shipment

title: For Trade:  Looking for AK, will trade scoped shotgun and scoped rifle
postcontent:
Will Trade my (2) all wood, scoped long guns for 1 good shooting AK.
(1st Gun)  is the Mossberg 500AB 12 gauge pump shotgun...it's a 6-shot and comes with a picatinny rail mounted Red Dot scope. The 500AB is the 500A Mossberg shotgun with some upgrades...specifically a Walnut stock VS. the various hardwood stocks found on the regular 500A model. This 500AB also has some metal etchings, that the 500A doesnt have ...and it has a 30" barrel. (Every part on this 500AB is interchangeable with the regular 500A)
This is a fixed full choke 30" barreled shotgun. 30 inches is a long range shotgun. Perfect for Deer and Water Fowl...and predators of any nature. You get the 75-100 yard reach of a rifle, with the spread pattern of a shotgun. Full choke means it keeps it's shot pattern tight over a long distance, so you get killing/stopping power at rifle like distances. It shoots bird and buck shot...and rifled slugs. It is chambered for 2 and 3/4" and 3.00" shells. It functions flawlessly and it looks good. The bore is beautiful inside...slick as a whistle. It also has a metal safety switch, not a plastic one like the newer Mossbergs. It has a Tasco Red Dot scope, a good one, that enables quick sholdering and accurate firing of shotgun. For those folks who don't know what a Red Dot scope is: You turn the switch on and the red dot is displayed in the scope lens...when you look thru the scope, wherever the dot is - is where the bullet goes. If you move your head, the red dot stays on the target your pointing the gun at and you can still see the dot as you move your head around. It makes for very quick and accurate shooting). I love this shotgun, and the new owner will too.
(2nd gun) is a Savage Arms MarkII .22 rifle...wood furniture..looks like brand new and functions flawlessly. Shoots more accurate than the Ruger 10/22 and the Marlin60..that's the truth. That's why it is scoped with a Barska 6.5-20x 50mm scope. This is a snipers scope...if you want the pupil at 75 yards away, you get the pupil. It's a bolt action rifle with (2) 10round clips. title: For Sale:  bushmaster ar 15 xm 15 e2s nib for sale
postcontent: Hello and thank you for checking out my riffle. Up for auction is a very nice Browning Model 71 lever action in .50 Alaskan, These rifles were orginally chambered in .348 Winchester. Gunsmiths wanted the Browning 71 due to its durability and strength when converting rifles to 50 Alaskan. This rifle has a half octagon half round barrel measuring at 34", an all steal Schnabel forend, the sights have not been clipped and the engraving on the barrel and action are beautiful. the stock also has a hidden compartment for holding 4 rounds. The .50 Alaskan is a wildcat cartridge developed by Harold Johnson and Harold Fuller of the Kenai Peninsula of Alaska in the 1950s. Johnson based the cartridge on the .348 Winchester in order to create a rifle capable of handling the large bears in Alaska. Design: Harold Johnson necked out the .348 Winchester case to accept a .510" diameter bullet, and Harold Fuller developed the barrel, marrying a .50 caliber barrel to an old Winchester Model 1886 rifle. Since the rifle was designed for use on Alaska’s great bears, Johnson cut 720-grain (47 g) boat-tail .50 BMG bullets in half, seating the 450-grain (29 g) rear half upside down in the fireformed .50-caliber case. It didn’t take Johnson long to find out that the 450-grain truncated shaped “solid” would shoot through a big brown bear from any direction, claiming in 1988, “I never recovered a slug from a bear or moose, no matter what angle the animal was shot at. Harold’s favorite load in the .50 Alaskan was 51.5 grains (3.34 g) of IMR-4198 with a Barnes 400-grain (26 g) flatnose ,jacketed bullet for about 2,100 ft/s (640 m/s) and just under 4,000 ft·lbf (5,400 J)of muzzle energy Shipping/handling is going to be $55 and insurance will be added at 1.75% of the item's value to cover potential damage or loss of the item in shipping. The price is for $1500 therefore, this item will still be subject to shipping and insurance charges. Because of additional paperwork and time to process the shipment

Primers are crimped AND sealed, and there is the typical sealant on the bullet itself - weatherproof stuff.  In case anybody wondered, the cupro-nickle jacket that makes it look like it's steel cased because of the color is actually about 90 percent copper and 10 percent nickle according to ammunition sources - for some reason even small amounts of nickle will make copper alloys look like steel.   It's magnetic, but cleared for use and import and NON-armor piercing according to ATF.  But the alloy itself is harder than typical copper jackets.  The addition of the nickle was meant to deter atmospheric corrosion in salt water environments.

title: For Sale:  PRIMER TRADE- small rifle(can be used for spp) for large pistol
postcontent:
In my last powder valley order, I anticipated buying a 1911 but I didnt anticipate how much Id shoot it. I ordered 7k tula small rifle and 3k tula large pistol. it should have been 5 of each. Ive been using small rifle almost exclusively in place of small pistol A- because of availability recently and B- to simplify things. primers that work for my 223 work for my 38, 357, 9mm  and vice versa. I have shot roughly 15,000 tula primers and they all go pop. small rifle is fine to use(of course downcharging the load and working up from there) in place of small pistol as long as you have a solid firing pin hit. title: For Sale/Trade:  Tactical Colt M4 carbine 22 AR15
postcontent:
For those of you who accidentally clicked on this ad thinking the rifle advertised shot .223/5.56nato - consider this:

*Unless you're shooting through a barrier a .22lr can be just as lethal as a .223, especially if it takes the 'ping-pong' approach in your target's body (ricocheting off bones carving tunnels through tissue and organs). There is more than one real life story of a .22lr entering the target at a 'non-kill' shot, such as the shoulder, and finding its way to a 'kill', such as the heart.

*a .223 round cost over 10x's as much and it is 10x's harder to find in stock. 

*Your wife is going to be able to defend herself more confidently with a .22lr and not be thrown off by recoil.

*This rifle is the exact same size and weight as a colt m4 5.56 ... the money you save on ammo alone would pay for this purchase if you intend on practicing and familiarizing yourself with AR15 combat.

title: For Sale:  1916 M91 "Peter The Great" Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
1916 M91 "Peter The Great" Mosin Nagant Rifle.

The barrel marks used on Mosin Nagants at the Tula and Izhevsk arsenals changed several times over the years and this is often related to the political situation in the country. The first major change was made in 1912 at Tula to commemorate the founding of the arsenal by Peter the Great in 1712. The wording was changed from "Imperial Tula Ordnance Factory" to "Tula Imperial Peter the Great Ordnance Factory" and the Imperial eagle was made larger and more detailed. During this period there was much unrest in Russia with one revolution having failed in 1905 and the next revolution of 1917 already brewing. 1712 was significant because it was also the year that St. Petersburg became the capital of Russia and the bicentennial was almost certainly used by the Tsar to emphasize the importance of his position to the wellbeing of the entire country.

After trials of several different repeating bolt action designs Russia adopted a new standard infantry rifle in 1891. It fires the 7.62x54r cartridge and is a combination of designs by Russian Sergei Mosin and Belgian Leon Nagant whose primary contribution was the magazine and feed system. The official Russian designation is “Three Line Rifle, Model of the Year 1891” but is more commonly known in the US as the Mosin Nagant M91. A “line” is a unit of measure equal to 1/10th of an inch. Production of the M91 took place at the Russian arsenals at Izhevsk, Tula, and Sestroryetsk. Due to a slow start in domestic production a contract was issued to the French arms company Chatellerault who built around 500,000 M91s. During WWI contracts were issued to the American firms of New England Westinghouse and Remington for 1.8 and 1.5 million rifles respectively. M91s were widely used in WWI and can be found with markings from many different European countries that purchased or captured them.

It hurts a little to part with it, and I may have trader's remorse, but I haven't used it much since graduating college. Great audio for such a little device, and it holds its charge well, IMO. They're going for about $120 in "acceptable" condition, and over $140 in "like new" condition on Amazon right now. This one's in pristine condition. Not a scratch on the screen.

HP SimpleSave 1 TB External HD
- Not much to say here. USB 2.0. Charger and cables. Software is on the HD.
It's worth $160 new on Amazon and $50-70 in various used conditions. I'm gonna go ahead and say it's worth about $60.
I found that 1 TB is a bit excessive for me. I have an older external HD, and it's suiting me fine.

I also have some odds and ends that I could throw in. About 50 rounds of Winchester SuperX .22 LR ammo, maybe some spare HDMI cords, and some really good pipe tobacco, if you would like to seal a deal with a smoke. Cornell & Diehl's Bayou Morning Flake--over 10 years old--and "Black Cordial" from a CA tobacco shop.

I'm in no real hurry to get rid of these or buy a shotgun. I just think my electronics aren't getting their full potential out of them, which is a shame--maybe you have an 870 or 500 that's getting similar treatment as well. That said, please don't lowball me. Haggling is ok, but please don't insult my intelligence.

Please text FIVE ONE ZERO-857-FOUR THREE 63 if you have a real offer and would like to arrange a meeting. Thanks.
